Unicode Unihan Database — Cantonese readings
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Files:    languages/yueh/table.go (generated)
Source:   https://www.unicode.org/Public/UCD/latest/ucd/Unihan.zip
License:  Unicode Terms of Use (https://www.unicode.org/copyright.html)

The Jyutping (Cantonese, tone-digit) reading table for the CJK Unified
Ideographs block (U+4E00..U+9FFF) is generated from the kCantonese field of
the Unicode Unihan Database. One primary reading per character.

The generator script is at internal/cmd/gen-unihan; it parses the
Unihan_Readings.txt file from the latest Unicode release.

Mandarin readings used to come from the same generator (kMandarin field).
They are now sourced from the vendored mozillazg/go-pinyin (per-character)
and mozillazg/phrase-pinyin-data (phrase-aware) tables — see the next
two attributions and internal/pinyin/NOTICE.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
go-pinyin + phrase-pinyin-data — Mandarin pinyin
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Files:    internal/pinyin/ (entire subtree)
Source:   https://github.com/mozillazg/go-pinyin
          https://github.com/mozillazg/phrase-pinyin-data
License:  MIT (both projects)

mozillazg/go-pinyin's source files are vendored under internal/pinyin
with no import-path rewriting (the package's exports work unmodified at
the new path). The phrase dictionary (pinyin.txt and overwrite.txt from
phrase-pinyin-data) is embedded under internal/pinyin/data and parsed
once at first use. languages/hani performs longest-match phrase lookup
against this dictionary before falling back to go-pinyin's per-character
table — this is what disambiguates polyphones such as 中 (zhōng / zhòng)
and 行 (xíng / háng) based on context.

See internal/pinyin/NOTICE for the full attribution and a list of files
that were not vendored.

