Aksharamukha — Indic script codepoint mappings
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Files:    internal/brahmic/{brahmi,sharada,modi,tirhuta,newa,taitham}.go
Source:   https://github.com/virtualvinodh/aksharamukha-python
License:  MIT

The per-codepoint romanization tables for:
  - Brahmi   (U+11000..U+1107F) — ancient Indian inscriptions
  - Sharada  (U+11180..U+111DF) — historical Kashmiri Śaiva texts
  - Modi    (U+11600..U+1165F) — historical Marathi
  - Tirhuta (U+11480..U+114DF) — Maithili
  - Newa    (U+11400..U+1147F) — Nepal Bhasa
  - Tai Tham (U+1A20..U+1AAF)  — Northern Thai, Tai Lue, Khün, Lao Tham

are derived from Aksharamukha's MIT-licensed mappings, aligned with
ISO 15919. No Aksharamukha source code is bundled — only the
codepoint-to-Latin tables for these scripts.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PyThaiNLP — Thai RTGS romanization algorithm (royin)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Files:    languages/thai/thai.go
Source:   https://github.com/PyThaiNLP/pythainlp
License:  Apache License 2.0

The Thai (RTGS-style) transliterator is a Go port of the rule-based
`royin` algorithm from PyThaiNLP. It implements the Thai Royal Institute's
Royal Thai General System of Transcription: pre-positioned vowel
reordering, multi-rune vowel patterns, thanthakhat silencing with
Sanskrit-cluster collapse, silent ห before sonorants, and tone-mark
dropping. No PyThaiNLP source code is bundled — the algorithm is
re-implemented in Go.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Lao — BGN/PCGN romanization algorithm
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Files:    languages/laoo/lao.go
Source:   BGN/PCGN 1966 Lao romanization (public standard document)
          https://github.com/wannaphong/LaoNLP (Apache 2.0)
License:  see below

The Lao transliterator at languages/laoo implements the BGN/PCGN 1966
standard — a public document from the U.S. Board on Geographic Names
and the U.K. Permanent Committee on Geographical Names.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unicode character names
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Files:    languages/cans/table.go, languages/cher/table.go
Source:   The Unicode Standard
License:  Unicode Terms of Use (https://www.unicode.org/copyright.html)

Romanization for Canadian Aboriginal Syllabics (U+1400..U+167F) and the
Cherokee syllabary (U+13A0..U+13FF, U+AB70..U+ABBF) are derived from the
syllable values embedded in Unicode character names.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

All other transliteration tables are hand-coded implementations of public
international standards (ISO 9, ISO 9985, ISO 15919, ISO 233-3, BGN/PCGN,
Revised Romanization of Korean, Hepburn, RTGS, SBL, Wylie) and are not
derived from copyrighted third-party data.
